---
import PageFooter from '../components/PageFooter.astro'
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro'
---
<Base
  title="design critique — example output"
  description="this is what you receive. a structured critique of a real landing page: hierarchy, typography, copy, color, and ranked priority fixes."
>
  <a href="/critique" class="back-btn">← critique</a>

  <section class="example">
    <div class="orb orb-1" aria-hidden="true"></div>

    <div class="content">
      <p class="eyebrow">example output</p>
      <h1>what you receive.</h1>
      <p class="lede">this is a real critique output. the brief was a B2B SaaS landing page for a project management tool. the same structure applies to every submission.</p>

      <div class="rule" aria-hidden="true"></div>

      <div class="report">

        <div class="section">
          <h2>first impression</h2>
          <p>the eye lands on the headline immediately — the size and weight do their job — but the hero image pulls attention right while the copy pulls left, and the visual tension reads as unresolved rather than dynamic. the overall feeling is "polished template" more than "calm, focused tool," which works against the brand promise.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
          <h2>what's working</h2>
          <p><strong>the headline copy is strong.</strong> "finally, a project tool your team will actually use" is specific, emotionally resonant, and speaks directly to the buyer's frustration. it earns its 56px treatment.</p>
          <p><strong>the alternating layout in the feature section creates rhythm.</strong> left-right-left-right breaks the monotony of vertical scroll without requiring the user to work to understand it. the 28px/16px type pairing in this section is the most readable on the page.</p>
          <p><strong>the pro card differentiation in pricing is correct.</strong> navy border plus a "most popular" badge is a well-established pattern that reduces cognitive load at the decision point. the visual anchor is doing real conversion work.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
          <h2>hierarchy &amp; layout</h2>
          <p>the split hero (copy left, image right) is a sound structure, but the execution undermines it. the headline is left-aligned at 56px, which creates strong leftward pull — the eye reads the headline, drops to the subheadline, reaches the CTAs, and then has to travel all the way right to reach the image. by the time a user gets there, they've already mentally moved on. consider centering the hero or reducing the image to a supporting role (smaller, partially cropped) so the eye doesn't have to make that journey.</p>
          <p>the feature section three-column grid has no hierarchy between columns. if "tasks" is the primary value driver, it needs to signal that — either through a larger icon, a bolder heading treatment, or a subtle background differentiation on that card. right now all three columns demand equal attention, which means none of them get it.</p>
          <p>the social proof bar is placed correctly (below the fold break, before feature depth), but the logo height inconsistency actively damages trust. misaligned logos look like a rush job, which is the opposite of what social proof is supposed to do.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
          <h2>typography &amp; spacing</h2>
          <p>the 14px nav links at #6b7280 are too light for their role. navigation is wayfinding infrastructure — dropping it to gray-500 at that size makes it feel de-prioritized to the point of invisibility, especially on lower-contrast displays.</p>
          <p>the "start free" button padding (8px top/bottom, 14px left/right) is tight enough to feel like an afterthought. primary CTAs need breathing room — 12–14px vertical padding is the baseline for a button that reads as confident.</p>
          <p>the pricing feature lists at 13px are the most fatiguing read on the page. sixteen items at 13px inside a card creates a wall of text. this isn't a spacing fix — it's a content problem — but typographically, even bumping to 14px with 1.6 line height would help.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
          <h2>color &amp; contrast</h2>
          <p>the navy / white / gray-500 palette is clean and appropriate for B2B — it signals reliability without being boring. no major accessibility flags at the primary text levels, though the #6b7280 body copy in the feature cards warrants a contrast check against white backgrounds (it sits close to the 4.5:1 WCAG AA threshold for 14px text).</p>
          <p>the pricing section's navy border on the pro card is the only moment of color accent on the page, which gives it appropriate weight. the "most popular" badge should use a warmer accent (amber, or a lighter tint) to create contrast against the card treatment — if it's also navy, it blends.</p>
          <p>the emotional tone skews cool and corporate. for a tool promising "calm workspace" for small teams, there's no warmth anywhere. one or two sections with a warm gray-50 or cream background would reinforce the brand message without breaking the palette.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
          <h2>copy &amp; content</h2>
          <p>the hero and feature copy are consistently good — specific, jargon-free, and benefit-led. "updates without the meetings" is the strongest feature heading on the page.</p>
          <p>the pricing feature lists are the biggest copy problem. free: 8 items. pro: 12. team: 16. this is a feature inventory, not a decision framework. users scanning pricing aren't asking "what features exist" — they're asking "what do I lose if I don't upgrade." reframe each tier around 3–4 outcome-oriented differentiators and cut the rest.</p>
          <p>the github social icon in the footer is a misalignment — this isn't a developer tool. github signals "open source" or "technical" to most users, muddying the positioning. remove it.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="section priority">
          <h2>priority fixes</h2>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <strong>fix the hero image quality and density.</strong>
              re-export the dashboard screenshot at 2x resolution and simplify the visible interface to 3–5 items maximum — the "calm workspace" promise lives or dies on what the product looks like at first glance. highest-impact single fix on the page.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>normalize the social proof logo heights.</strong>
              set a fixed optical height of 24–28px for all logos using <code>max-height</code> with optical adjustment per logo — this takes 20 minutes and converts what reads as careless into a credibility signal.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>reduce pricing feature lists to 4 items per tier, outcome-focused.</strong>
              rewrite each as a clear differentiator (what you gain at each step up), remove the feature dump, and the pricing section becomes a decision aid rather than a comparison table users abandon.
            </li>
          </ol>
        </div>

      </div>

      <div class="cta-row">
        <a href="https://critique.janicequach.workers.dev" class="cta">submit your design → $75</a>
        <a href="/critique" class="back-link">← back to critique</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <PageFooter theme="contact" />
</Base>

<style>
  .example {
    position: relative;
    min-height: 100vh;
    padding: 8rem 2rem 6rem;
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
  }

  .orb-1 {
    position: fixed;
    width: 500px;
    height: 500px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    pointer-events: none;
    background: radial-gradient(circle at 40% 40%, rgba(220, 207, 185, 0.28), transparent 70%);
    top: -100px;
    right: -80px;
    z-index: 0;
  }

  .content {
    position: relative;
    z-index: 1;
    max-width: 680px;
    width: 100%;
  }

  .eyebrow {
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.15em;
    color: rgba(42, 37, 32, 0.5);
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }

  h1 {
    font-size: clamp(2rem, 5vw, 3.25rem);
    line-height: 1.1;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    color: #2a2520;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }

  .lede {
    font-size: 1rem;
    color: rgba(42, 37, 32, 0.6);
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
  }

  .rule {
    width: 48px;
    height: 1px;
    background: rgba(42, 37, 32, 0.2);
    margin-bottom: 3rem;
  }

  .report {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 2.5rem;
  }

  .section h2 {
    font-family: "DM Serif Display", Georgia, serif;
    font-size: 1.125rem;
    font-weight: 400;
    color: #2a2520;
    margin-bottom: 0.875rem;
    padding-bottom: 0.5rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(42, 37, 32, 0.1);
  }

  .section p {
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    color: rgba(42, 37, 32, 0.72);
    line-height: 1.8;
    margin-bottom: 0.875rem;
  }

  .section p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  .section strong {
    color: #2a2520;
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .priority ol {
    list-style: none;
    counter-reset: priority;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 1.25rem;
  }

  .priority li {
    counter-increment: priority;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 2rem 1fr;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    color: rgba(42, 37, 32, 0.72);
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  .priority li::before {
    content: counter(priority);
    font-family: "DM Serif Display", Georgia, serif;
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    color: rgba(42, 37, 32, 0.25);
    line-height: 1.6;
    text-align: right;
  }

  code {
    font-family: "SF Mono", "Fira Code", monospace;
    font-size: 0.875em;
    background: rgba(42, 37, 32, 0.07);
    padding: 0.1em 0.35em;
    border-radius: 3px;
  }

  .cta-row {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 2rem;
    margin-top: 3.5rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }

  .cta {
    display: inline-block;
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: 0.02em;
    color: #f4f1eb;
    background: #2a2520;
    padding: 1rem 2.5rem;
    border-radius: 8px;
    text-decoration: none;
    transition: background 0.2s ease, transform 0.2s cubic-bezier(0.16, 1, 0.3, 1);
  }

  .cta:hover {
    background: #45403a;
    transform: translateY(-2px);
  }

  .back-link {
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    color: rgba(42, 37, 32, 0.5);
    text-decoration: none;
    transition: color 0.2s ease;
  }

  .back-link:hover {
    color: rgba(42, 37, 32, 0.8);
  }

  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .example {
      padding: 6rem 1.5rem 4rem;
    }

    .cta-row {
      flex-direction: column;
      align-items: flex-start;
      gap: 1rem;
    }
  }
</style>
